{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:16:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:16:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13090"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13090"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.35,0.03,0.03,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108860"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13090"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91224"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2231"},{"type":"tags","id":"2474"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108860"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a one-month history of a non-productive cough, night sweats, and an unintentional weight loss of seven kilograms. She has a history of cystic fibrosis and is being considered for lung transplant. She was born in Australia and has no known history of recent travel. She works as a soil scientist and her work often involves assessing soil samples in damp forest settings. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears cachectic. Her blood pressure is 120/88 mmHg, pulse rate 77/min, temperature 38.1\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 15/min, and oxygen saturation 89% on room air. Auscultation of the chest reveals scattered crackles in the right lower lobe. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 125 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 8.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils 0.1 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (0.04-0.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal immunoglobulin E 45 IU/mL (0-100). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum galactomannan test: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest CT: right upper lobe cavitary lesion and scattered nodules. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESputum cultures: pending.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Mycobacterium avium complex","Staphylococcus aureus","Haemophilus influenzae","Aspergillus fumigatus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECystic fibrosis (CF) is an autosomal recessive, multisystem disorder due to a pathogenic mutation of the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR) gene. Patients are at increased risk of pulmonary infection due to mucous plugging caused by thickened secretions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation, including a non-productive cough, night sweats, weight loss, and a cavitary lesion on chest CT, is highly suggestive of an infection by \u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium avium complex (MAC)\u003C/strong\u003E. MAC is commonly found in soil and water (which highlights the relevance of her occupation and her work) and can cause pulmonary disease, especially in individuals with underlying lung conditions such as cystic fibrosis. The presence of scattered nodules further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms, including cavitary lung lesions. However, the patient lacks significant risk factors for tuberculosis, such as recent travel to endemic areas or known exposure to active tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a common pathogen in cystic fibrosis patients and can cause pulmonary infections. However, the clinical presentation and imaging findings are more consistent with a mycobacterial infection rather than a bacterial one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is another bacterium that can cause respiratory infections, but it is less likely to cause cavitary lesions and the systemic symptoms described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAspergillus fumigatus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pulmonary infections and allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis in cystic fibrosis patients with cavitary lesions on chest imaging, however this diagnosis is less likely given the normal eosinophil count, immunoglobulin E levels and serum Galactomannan test in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cystic fibrosis (CF) is an autosomal recessive, multisystem disorder.","Patients with cystic fibrosis are at increased risk of pulmonary infection due to mucous plugging caused by thickened secretions.","Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC) is commonly found in soil and water and can cause pulmonary disease in individuals with underlying lung conditions such as cystic fibrosis."],"references":["Daley CL. Mycobacterium avium Complex Disease. Microbiology Spectrum. 2017 Apr 21;5(2):10.1128/microbiolspec.tnmi7-0045\u20132017.","Blanchard AC, Waters VJ. Opportunistic Pathogens in Cystic Fibrosis: Epidemiology and Pathogenesis of Lung Infection. Vol. 11, Journal of the Pediatric Infectious Diseases Society. 2022. p. S3\u201312.","Aspergillosis. In: Royal College of Pathologists of Australasia (RCPA) Manual [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.rcpa.edu.au/Manuals/RCPA-Manual/Clinical-Presentations-and-Diagnoses/A/Aspergillosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91224"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13090"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91224"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T21:02:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T21:04:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108860"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}